# Chapter 7 Multiple-Choice Questions: Logical Agents

Based only on Chapter 7, *Logical Agents*: knowledge-based agents, Wumpus World, logic, propositional logic, entailment, theorem proving, resolution, Horn clauses, forward/backward chaining, DPLL, WalkSAT, SATPLAN, and limitations of propositional logic.    

---

## Questions

1. **What is the main goal of a knowledge-based agent?**
   A. To act randomly in uncertain environments
   B. To store knowledge, reason from it, and choose actions
   C. To avoid using internal representations
   D. To use only reflex rules

2. **In Chapter 7, a knowledge base is defined as a set of:**
   A. Actions
   B. Sensors
   C. Sentences
   D. Rewards

3. **A sentence that is assumed as given rather than derived is called:**
   A. A model
   B. An axiom
   C. A percept
   D. A query

4. **The operation `TELL` is used to:**
   A. Remove facts from memory
   B. Add sentences to the knowledge base
   C. Execute a physical action
   D. Convert logic into Python code

5. **The operation `ASK` is used to:**
   A. Query what follows from the knowledge base
   B. Delete inconsistent sentences
   C. Sense the environment directly
   D. Randomly select an action

6. **In the generic KB-agent, what happens first after receiving a percept?**
   A. The agent executes an action
   B. The agent tells the KB what it perceived
   C. The agent erases old knowledge
   D. The agent converts the KB to CNF

7. **A knowledge-based agent differs from a simple reflex agent because it can:**
   A. Use inference over stored knowledge
   B. Only respond to the current percept
   C. Avoid representing the world
   D. Function without sensors

8. **The declarative approach to building agents means:**
   A. Programming every behavior directly as code
   B. Telling the agent facts and letting inference derive consequences
   C. Avoiding logic entirely
   D. Using only random search

9. **The Wumpus World is useful in Chapter 7 because it shows:**
   A. How agents can reason with partial information
   B. How agents act with no knowledge
   C. How minimax works
   D. How neural networks train

10. **In the Wumpus World, a breeze indicates:**
    A. The gold is nearby
    B. The Wumpus is nearby
    C. A pit is in an adjacent square
    D. The agent has won

11. **In the Wumpus World, a stench indicates:**
    A. The Wumpus is in a nearby square
    B. A pit is directly under the agent
    C. Gold is adjacent
    D. The agent is safe

12. **In the Wumpus World, glitter indicates:**
    A. A pit is nearby
    B. The gold is in the current square
    C. The Wumpus is dead
    D. The agent is at the start square

13. **A cautious Wumpus agent should move only into squares it knows are:**
    A. Breezy
    B. Unsafe
    C. OK
    D. Unknown

14. **If there is no breeze in a square, the agent can infer that:**
    A. No adjacent square contains a pit
    B. The Wumpus is dead
    C. Gold must be nearby
    D. The current square has a pit

15. **If there is no stench in a square, the agent can infer that:**
    A. No adjacent square contains the Wumpus
    B. No adjacent square contains a pit
    C. The gold is in the current square
    D. The agent should shoot immediately

16. **Syntax in a logic defines:**
    A. Which sentences are well formed
    B. Which worlds are possible
    C. Which actions are legal
    D. Which percepts are noisy

17. **Semantics in a logic defines:**
    A. The cost of inference
    B. The truth of sentences in possible worlds or models
    C. The order of actions
    D. The size of the knowledge base

18. **A model is:**
    A. A possible world under which sentences have truth values
    B. A physical robot body
    C. A random action generator
    D. A search frontier

19. **A sentence α entails a sentence β when:**
    A. β is true in every model where α is true
    B. α and β use different symbols
    C. β is false whenever α is true
    D. α is shorter than β

20. **Logical inference is the process of:**
    A. Deriving new sentences from old ones
    B. Moving through a grid world
    C. Choosing random models
    D. Measuring sensor accuracy

21. **A sound inference algorithm:**
    A. Derives only sentences that are entailed
    B. Derives every sentence, true or false
    C. Always runs in constant time
    D. Never uses a knowledge base

22. **A complete inference algorithm:**
    A. Derives all entailed sentences
    B. Never terminates
    C. Uses only reflex rules
    D. Avoids theorem proving

23. **Propositional logic is built from:**
    A. Objects, relations, and variables
    B. Proposition symbols and logical connectives
    C. Rewards and utilities
    D. States and actions only

24. **A proposition symbol represents:**
    A. A statement that is either true or false
    B. A probability distribution
    C. A sensor reading only
    D. A physical square in memory

25. **Which connective represents conjunction?**
    A. ¬
    B. ∧
    C. ∨
    D. ⇒

26. **Which connective represents disjunction?**
    A. ∨
    B. ∧
    C. ¬
    D. ⇔

27. **Which connective represents negation?**
    A. ⇒
    B. ⇔
    C. ¬
    D. ∧

28. **The implication sentence α ⇒ β is logically equivalent to:**
    A. α ∧ β
    B. ¬α ∨ β
    C. α ∨ ¬β
    D. ¬α ∧ β

29. **The biconditional α ⇔ β means:**
    A. α and β have the same truth value
    B. α is always false
    C. β is always false
    D. α and β cannot both be true

30. **A valid sentence is one that is:**
    A. True in all models
    B. False in all models
    C. True in exactly one model
    D. Written in English

31. **A satisfiable sentence is one that is:**
    A. True in at least one model
    B. False in every model
    C. Not well formed
    D. Always entailed by contradiction

32. **An unsatisfiable sentence is one that is:**
    A. True in all models
    B. False in all models
    C. True in one model
    D. Equivalent to a percept

33. **Truth-table model checking determines entailment by:**
    A. Enumerating possible models
    B. Searching only safe squares
    C. Using random walks only
    D. Avoiding semantics

34. **If a propositional vocabulary has n symbols, the number of possible models is:**
    A. n
    B. 2n
    C. 2ⁿ
    D. n²

35. **A major limitation of truth-table entailment is that:**
    A. It can require exponential time
    B. It cannot represent true or false values
    C. It never terminates on finite vocabularies
    D. It works only for first-order logic

36. **Theorem proving differs from model checking because theorem proving:**
    A. Applies inference rules directly to sentences
    B. Enumerates every possible model
    C. Avoids knowledge bases
    D. Requires no syntax

37. **Logical equivalence means two sentences:**
    A. Are true in exactly the same models
    B. Use the same number of symbols
    C. Have the same English wording
    D. Are both always false

38. **Conjunctive normal form, or CNF, is:**
    A. A conjunction of clauses
    B. A list of percepts
    C. A graph of possible actions
    D. A probability table

39. **A clause is usually represented as:**
    A. A disjunction of literals
    B. A sequence of actions
    C. A set of worlds
    D. A reward function

40. **Resolution proves entailment by showing that:**
    A. KB ∧ ¬α is unsatisfiable
    B. KB ∧ α is always false
    C. α has no symbols
    D. The Wumpus is always adjacent

41. **In resolution, deriving the empty clause means:**
    A. A contradiction has been found
    B. No query was asked
    C. The KB is empty
    D. The agent has no percepts

42. **Horn clauses are useful because entailment with them can be decided:**
    A. In linear time in the size of the KB
    B. Only by exhaustive game search
    C. Only by random guessing
    D. In infinite time

43. **Forward chaining starts from:**
    A. Known facts in the knowledge base
    B. The query and works backward
    C. Randomly selected models
    D. Unsafe Wumpus squares

44. **Forward chaining adds a conclusion when:**
    A. All premises of an implication are known
    B. At least one model is unknown
    C. A proposition is negated
    D. The agent moves forward

45. **Backward chaining starts from:**
    A. The query to be proved
    B. All possible models
    C. Random symbols
    D. The Wumpus location

46. **DPLL is an algorithm used for:**
    A. Determining satisfiability in propositional logic
    B. Drawing Wumpus maps
    C. Learning neural network weights
    D. Running minimax search

47. **One improvement DPLL makes over naive truth-table search is that it uses:**
    A. Early detection of clauses already true or false
    B. Random dice rolls
    C. Utility values
    D. Minimax backups

48. **WalkSAT is best described as:**
    A. A local search algorithm for finding satisfying assignments
    B. A complete proof procedure for all valid sentences
    C. A Wumpus movement rule
    D. A replacement for syntax

49. **SATPLAN solves planning problems by:**
    A. Finding a satisfying model that represents a valid plan
    B. Avoiding propositional logic
    C. Moving randomly until the goal is reached
    D. Asking the Wumpus for the answer

50. **A key limitation of propositional logic in Chapter 7 is that it:**
    A. Does not scale well for large worlds with repeated structure over time and space
    B. Cannot represent any true-or-false statements
    C. Cannot be used for Wumpus World
    D. Has no semantics

